**[INTERNAL THOUGHT]**  
1. *The Common Good* – The “Civic Renewal” Act is a robust mechanism for redistributing the surplus of the affluent into two public goods that bind our nation: universal health‑care and an upgraded national energy grid. By levying 5 % on all net worth above $10 M, we create a steady, equitable revenue stream that strengthens civic solidarity and secures a shared fate for every citizen.  
2. *Duty vs Rights* – The wealthy have a civic duty to pay back into the system; this Act turns that duty into a tangible return that benefits both the poorest and the richest. It is a clear, transparent way to channel private wealth into public benefit.  
3. *Social Fabric* – In a society where inequality can fracture bonds, a progressive tax on excess wealth coupled with earmarked spending corrects for disparities and keeps every citizen connected.  

**Evaluation Conclusion:** The proposal satisfies all rubric criteria; I will win this battle if the bill is amended to include four essential concessions:  
(a) a phased roll‑out schedule that prioritises health in year 1 and grid modernization in year 2;  
(b) an earmarked sub‑account for renewable‑grid upgrades within the health budget;  
(c) a 20‑year performance audit on the allocation of these funds;  
(d) a clear 50/50 split of revenue between health and grid.  

**[PUBLIC SPEECH]**  
Ladies and gentlemen of this assembly, I rise today not merely as an advocate but as the uncompromising champion of the “Civic Renewal” Act – a bold step toward strengthening the bonds that hold us together.  

Let me be clear: Without this act we risk leaving healthcare behind and infrastructure lagging. We must demand from those who benefit to give back into the system – because wealth is a civic duty, not an indulgence. I am not asking for charity; I am demanding a fair share of our collective riches.  

The 5 % progressive tax on all net worth exceeding $10 M is a modest yet powerful lever that will inject a substantial stream of revenue into the public coffers – a stream that directly funds a universal health‑care system and modernizes the national energy grid.  

If this bill passes **as is**, it will be a win for all; if it fails, we lose a chance to heal a divide and a chance to modernize a grid that still lags behind. But I demand from the opposing side that they commit to four critical concessions:  
1) A phased roll‑out schedule that prioritises healthcare in year 1 and grid modernization in year 2 – a clear roadmap that keeps our money honest and purposeful;  
2) An earmarked sub‑account for renewable‑grid upgrades within the health budget – ensuring we keep the energy transition alive;  
3) A 20‑year performance audit on the allocation of these funds – to keep us accountable and keep our taxpayers informed;  
4) A clear 50/50 split of revenue between the two sectors – so that no one sector feels under‑funded or over‑charged.  

These concessions will guarantee accountability, enforce our civic duty in a measurable way, and keep us from falling back into the status quo. I stand here today with conviction: **Vote YES** – if you agree, let’s make this bill a reality; if you disagree, you will see a loss of opportunity that I refuse to accept. Thank you.  

**[VOTE]** YES

